In [2]:
payroll_query = """
    WITH payrolls AS
      (SELECT teamID, yearID, sum(salary) AS payroll
      FROM Salaries
      GROUP BY teamID, yearID)
    SELECT Teams.teamID,
          Teams.yearID,
          Teams.lgID,
          payroll,
          ((W*1.0/G)*100) as win_percentage
    FROM payrolls, Teams
    WHERE payrolls.yearID = Teams.yearID and
          payrolls.teamID = Teams.teamID
      """
result = pd.read_sql(payroll_query, conn)
result

figure, axis = plt.subplots(ncols=7, nrows=5, figsize=(30, 18))
for i in range(5):
  for j in range(7):
    idx = i*7 + j
    axis[i, j].plot(pt.iloc[idx]['yearID'], pt.iloc[idx]['payroll'])
    axis[i, j].set_title(pt.iloc[idx].name)

Problem 4

In [5]:
group_names = ['group1','group2','group3','group4','group5']
result['categories'] = pd.cut(result['yearID'], 5, labels=group_names)
groups = result.groupby('categories')
In [6]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(5, 1, figsize=(10, 50))
i = 0
for g in group_names:
  curg = groups.get_group(g)
  paylist = list(curg['payroll'])
  winlist = list(curg['win_percentage'])
  curgroup = sns.regplot(x = paylist, y = winlist, ax=axes[i])
  for row in curg.itertuples():
    curgroup.text(row.payroll, row.win_percentage, row.teamID)
  curgroup.set_title(g)
  i+=1

Question 2

According to the graph shown above, it is pretty clear that teams with better win rate tends to get paid more.

NYA standsouts for being particularly good at paying for wins across these time periods. It's always on the right end of the graph. Meaning that they got paied good for most of their games.

Looking at all the data points that represent OAK, I would conclude that OAK is one of those teams that did not get paid well. It tends to get paid less than all other contreparts that have the same win rate.

pay_std = list(result.groupby('yearID')['payroll'].std())
paylist=[]
for index, row in result.iterrows():
  curyear = row.yearID
  paylist.append((row.payroll - pay[curyear-1990])/pay_std[curyear-1990])

result['standardized_payroll'] = paylist
result

Question 3

By calculating the standardized payroll, we derive a dataset with mean centered at 0 and spread out in both negative and positive direction. Also, the process of problem 5 normalizes all the data points, making the new datapoints in the plot more standardized, i.e. the plot for problem 6 is more to scale.

By doing so, we culd easily see if a team is payed above or below average. Thus, we could say that doing so make it easier to do comparisons between data points.

Question 4

Form question 2 and 3 we noticed that there's a strong correlation between payroll and win rate of the teams. Teams with better win rate tends to get paid more. Problem 8 looks into how efficient, i.e. how well the money paid off, for each of the five teams are over the past 25 years. Teams generally get a high efficiency value when they won a lot relative to the money thet got paid. This graph provide us a better look into the performance of each team comparing to that of question 2 and 3.

AS shown by this plot, OAK have a relativey good efficiency value comparing to all other 4 teams throught all these years. According to what I got from question 2, OAK was not paid well because all its counterparts who have the same win rate all got paid better. Plot 8 somehow supports that oppinion towards OAK. OAK's high effaciency supports that they won more relative to the money got paid.
